{
  "texts": [
    "Neither the hidden influence nor the bypassing rationality conceptions offers a way to capture all cases of manipulation and only cases of manipulation.",
    "This led some to wonder whether there is any conceptualisation of manipulation at all that is satisfactory given a narrow criterion for appropriateness (cf.",
    "Coons & Weber, 2014a; Klenk & Jongepier, 2022b).",
    "However, disjunctive conceptions for identifying manipulation may be a solution.",
    "For example, in their discussion of the ethical alignment of language agents, Kenton et al. (2021) reflect on the diversity of philosophical accounts of manipulation and opt for a disjunctive conception that combines several criteria that are discussed in the philosophical literature."
  ]
}